SIMPLE: imprecation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Imprecation
<hw>Im`pre*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>imprecatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>impr⟦eacute⟧cation</ets>.]</ety>
<def>The act of imprecating, or invoking evil upon any one; a prayer
that a curse or calamity may fall on any one; a curse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men cowered like slaves before such horrid
<qex>imprecations</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Motley.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Malediction; curse; execration; anathema. See
<er>Malediction</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Imprecatory</ent>⟦br⟧
